      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H} \vdash  t' : S$}
      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H}^- \vdash  t' : S$}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (app$^\star $)}
      \TrinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} \vdash  (t\ t') : T$}
    \end {bprooftree}






    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H} \vdash  t : \text {Prop}$}
      \LeftLabel {\small  ($\exists \alpha $)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} \vdash  \exists \alpha .t : \text {Prop}$}
    \end {bprooftree}
    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {}
      \LeftLabel {\small  ($<$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} \vdash  \beta  < \alpha  : \text {Prop}$}
    \end {bprooftree}

Domains/types in \mu HOL^{ex} are defined as follows, where D ranges over a countable set of base domains, and v ranges over the set \{+, -, \star \} of variance annotations.
       \begin {align*}       S, T &::= D\ |\ S \to ^v T\\       P &::= \text {Prop}\ |\ T \to ^v P     \end {align*}   
  The base domains would be specified in a signature.

We write \mathcal {H}^- for the simple type environment satisfying:

x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}

The one-step \beta -reduction relation on expression, \longrightarrow _\beta , is defined inductively as follows.
       (\lambda (x^v:T).t)\ t' \longrightarrow _\beta  t[t'/x]   

       \begin {align*}            t_1\ t_2 &\longrightarrow _\beta  t_1'\ t_2 & \text {if } t_1 \longrightarrow _\beta  t_1'\\     t_1\ t_2 &\longrightarrow _\beta  t_1\ t_2' & \text {if } t_2 \longrightarrow _\beta  t_2'\\     t_1 \Rightarrow  t_2 &\longrightarrow _\beta  t_1' \Rightarrow  t_2 & \text {if } t_1 \longrightarrow _\beta  t_1'\\     t_1 \Rightarrow  t_2 &\longrightarrow _\beta  t_1 \Rightarrow  t_2' & \text {if } t_2 \longrightarrow _\beta  t_2'\\     \lambda (x^v : T).t &\longrightarrow _\beta  \lambda (x^v : T).t' & \text {if } t \longrightarrow _\beta  t'\\     \forall (x : T).t &\longrightarrow _\beta  \forall (x : T).t' & \text {if } t \longrightarrow _\beta  t'\\     \mu ^\alpha (x : P).t &\longrightarrow _\beta  \mu ^\alpha (x : P).t' & \text {if } t \longrightarrow _\beta  t'\\     \exists \alpha .t &\longrightarrow _\beta  \exists \alpha .t' & \text {if } t \longrightarrow _\beta  t'        \end {align*}

\beta -reduction of \mu HOL^{ex} expressions is strongly normalising.
670#253unstable-253.xmlProof20241216Chris Purdy We show this by reduction to the typed \lambda -calculus. Domains are translated by removing the variance annotation from arrow domains:
\begin {align*} \lfloor D \rfloor &= D\\ \lfloor \text {Prop} \rfloor &= \text {Prop}\\ \lfloor S \to ^v T \rfloor &= \lfloor S \rfloor \to \lfloor T \rfloor \end {align*}
\mu HOL^{ex} expressions are translated to \lambda -expressions inductively as follows, where i : \text {Prop} \to \text {Prop} \to \text {Prop} and l : \text {Prop} are constants.
\begin {align*} \lfloor x \rfloor &= x\\ \lfloor \alpha < \beta \rfloor &= l\\ \lfloor t_1\ t_2 \rfloor &= \lfloor t_1 \rfloor \ \lfloor t_2 \rfloor \\ \lfloor t_1 \Rightarrow t_2 \rfloor &= i\ \lfloor t_1 \rfloor \ \lfloor t_2 \rfloor \\ \lfloor \lambda (x^v : T).t \rfloor &= \lambda (x : \lfloor T \rfloor ).\lfloor t \rfloor \\ \lfloor \forall (x : T).t \rfloor &= \lfloor t \rfloor \\ \lfloor \mu ^\alpha (x : T).t \rfloor &= \lfloor t \rfloor \\ \lfloor \exists \alpha .t \rfloor &= \lfloor t \rfloor \end {align*}
We have that t_1 \longrightarrow _\beta t_2 implies \lfloor t_1 \rfloor \longrightarrow _\beta \lfloor t_2 \rfloor , so we are done by contradiction; if \beta -reduction of \mu HOL^{ex} terms were not strongly normalising, then typed \lambda -calculus would not be.

This system is used to carve out the "well-varianced" formulae from all those allowed by the definition of \mu HOL^{ex} syntax.


